Hi Chuck,

I&#39;m not so sure I did as well with your question as I might have.

The schwa I was talking about occurs as the a in ago, the e in agent, the i
in sanity, the o in comply, and the u in focus. In some dictionaries it is
also the u in up. In other dictionaries, a different symbol is used for the
u in up. So there is a possible distinction between the two sounds. However,
they are close.

Quickscript does not distinguish between the two sounds. I believe it uses
the same symbol, number 36, for the u sound of up and the a sound in ago.
This is apparently not the case for Shavian, which does distinguish the
sounds.

The following is a copy of 3/16/2002 correspondence on this subject:

&quot;C. Paige Gabhart&quot; wrote:
[omitted text]
&gt;
&gt; When Read developed Quikscript, he dropped the two separate characters for
the
&gt; pairs &quot;Err&quot; and &quot;Array&quot; and &quot;Up&quot; and &quot;Ado&quot; which appeared in Shavian.
This was
&gt; done after extensive correspondence in Shavian between English speaking
countries
&gt; around the world.  I assume he decided that the distinction was not as
clear as he
&gt; first thought it was from his British perspective, and that it added a
needless
&gt; complexity to the alphabet.  On the other hand, he added &quot;Wh&quot; to
Quikscript, which
&gt; he learned many people still do distinguish and feel quite strongly about
it.
&gt;
&gt; I have not followed the discussion closely regarding stress, but if that
is the
&gt; primary distinction between &quot;Ado&quot; and &quot;Up&quot; and &quot;Array&quot; and &quot;Err&quot;, then I
believe
&gt; Read was correct in dropping the &quot;stressed&quot; characters.  I have been using
&gt; Quikscript for over twenty-five years, and I have never missed &quot;Err&quot; or
&quot;Up&quot;.  In
&gt; fact, I was not sure what sounds they were supposed to represent as I
could not
&gt; hear any distinction in the way I pronounced the applicable words.  It had
never
&gt; occurred to me that the difference was supposedly one of stress.  My
reaction is
&gt; that certain vowels will be stressed as a result of where they appear in a
given
&gt; word  and as a result of the consonants surrounding them.  We do not have
other
&gt; letters whose only difference is stress, and I do not think stress should
be
&gt; represented by a different character in the alphabet.
&gt;
&gt; The dictionary I have here at home is Webster&#39;s Ninth New Collegiate.  I
looked up
&gt; &quot;Ado&quot;, &quot;Up&quot;, &quot;Array&quot; and &quot;Err&quot;, and the opening vowel sound of all four
words is
&gt; represented by a schwa.  The difference in stress is shown by an accent,
not by a
&gt; different phonetic symbol.  The word &quot;abut&quot;, which Hugh recently mentioned
in a
&gt; post as needing &quot;Up&quot;, rather than &quot;Ado&quot; for its second vowel is also
listed with a
&gt; schwa.  Thus, I find no reason to suppose that Read somehow needlessly
simplified
&gt; Quikscript&#39;s ability to accurately represent English.  And I have to
respectfully
&gt; disagree with you that these are separate and distinct sounds.
&gt;
&gt; &gt; Ado and Up are distinct sounds as are Err and Array.
&gt; &gt; quickscript combines err and array which makes it harder to express
&gt; &gt; certain things, IMHO.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Peace,
&gt; &gt; Star


